{{Infobox artist | name = Ken Sugimori | native_name = 杉森 建 | image =<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Artist, Ken Sugimori.png]] --> | imagesize = | alt = | caption = Ken Sugimori in 2010 | birth_name = Sugimori Ken | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|1|27}} | birth_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Japan]]ese | field = [[Game designer|Video game design]] | training = | movement = | works = ''[[Pokémon]]''; ''[[Pulseman]]''; ''[[Drill Dozer]]'' | influenced by = | influenced = | awards = | website = }}
{{nihongo|'''Ken Sugimori'''|杉森 建|Sugimori Ken}} (born January 27, 1966 in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]) is a Japanese video game designer, illustrator, [[mangaka|manga artist]], and [[Video game director (disambiguation)|director]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/06/05/manga-artist-game-designer-ken-sugimoris-work-pokmon/|title=From Manga Artist To Game Designer: Ken Sugimori’s Work Before Pokémon - Siliconera|date=5 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> He is most famous as the character designer and art director for the ''[[Pokémon]]'' franchise. Sugimori is also credited with the art direction for other titles, including ''[[Pulseman]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/100/1006614p1.html|title=Pulseman Review|last=Thomas|first=Lucas|date=23 July 2009|publisher=IGN. [[News Corporation]]|accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> Sugimori drew and finalized all of the original 151 Pokémon.<ref name=Gifford>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesetwatch.com/2008/04/column_game_mag_weaseling_just.php|title='Game Mag Weaseling': Just Checking In|last=Gifford|first=Kevin|date=7 April 2008|publisher=GameSetWatch. Think Services|accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> He has worked on the various ''Pokémon'' films, trading cards, and other games like the ''[[Super Smash Bros. (series)|Super Smash Bros.]]'' series.
==Career== From early 1981 until 1986, Sugimori illustrated a gaming [[fanzine]] called [[Game Freak (magazine)|''Game Freak'']], which had been started by [[Satoshi Tajiri]].<ref name=Gifford/> Sugimori discovered the magazine in a [[dōjinshi]] shop, and decided to get involved.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kohler|first=Chris|title=Power-up: How Japanese Video Games Gave the World an Extra Life|publisher=[[BradyGames]]|year=2004|page=238|isbn=0-7440-0424-1}}</ref> Eventually, the two decided to pitch an [[arcade game]] design idea to [[Namco]]; they reworked [[Game Freak]] into a development company and produced ''[[Mendel Palace]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/blogEntry?bId=8825137&publicUserId=4547783|title=25 Sorta Significant Famicom Games: #19|last=Barnholt|first=Ray|date=30 July 2008|publisher=[[1UP.com]]. [[UGO Networks]]|accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> Sugimori is most famous as the character designer and art director for the ''[[Pokémon]]'' franchise and designed the first 151 Pokémon with [[Atsuko Nishida]], [[Motofumi Fujiwara]], and [[Shigeki Morimoto]]. He has worked on the various ''Pokémon'' movies, trading cards, and other games.
For [[Pokémon Black and White|''Pokémon Black'' and ''White'']], Sugimori directed a team of 17 people in designing new characters for the games, though he always drew the final designs. He drew much of his inspiration from observing animals in [[aquarium]]s and [[zoo]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Iwata|first=Satoru|title=DSで２作目の完全新作をつくること|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/interview/irbj/vol1/index.html|work=Iwata Asks|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=23 September 2010|authorlink=Satoru Iwata|location=[[Kyoto, Japan]]|page=2|language=Japanese|year=2010}}</ref> Sugimori has also written and illustrated original [[manga]], including one which was distributed with pre-orders of [[Pokémon Mystery Dungeon: Explorers of Time and Explorers of Darkness|''Pokémon Mystery Dungeon: Explorers of Time'' and ''Explorers of Darkness'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ds.ign.com/articles/859/859436p1.html?RSSwhen2008-03-13_142300&RSSid=859436|title=Pokemon Pre-Order Offer|last=Staff|date=13 March 2008|publisher=IGN. [[News Corporation]]|accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> When he begins a new character, his process normally involves making a rough sketch, then tracing it onto film paper while polishing it and making the illustration more professional looking. After that, he draws the character many times, changing its proportions until he is satisfied.<ref>{{cite news|title=Game Freak on Pokemon! One of them was Rayquaza [RAE-KUA-ZAH] Ken Sugimori's design of rayquaza was exceptional like all of the others, he spent much dedicated time into his designs like mewtwo. |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=91965&skip=yes|accessdate=25 September 2010|newspaper=[[Computer and Video Games]]|date=30 May 2003|agency=[[Future Publishing]]}}</ref> When designing a new Pokemon, Sugimori stated that "I do feel that I always want to show new Pokemon that people have never seen before. To do that, I think of ways that I can surprise the players."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shepperd|first1=Chris|title=Pearls of Wisdom|work=Nintendo Power|issue=215|publisher=Nintendo|date=May 2017}}</ref>
