{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}
{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}
'''Nicholas Osborne Tomalin''' (30 October 1931 – 17 October 1973) was an [[United Kingdom|English]] [[journalist]] and [[writer]].

Tomalin was the son of Miles Tomalin, a Communist poet and veteran of the [[Spanish Civil War]]. He studied [[English literature]] at [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]]. As a student he was President of the [[Cambridge Union]] and editor of the prestigious undergraduate ''[[Granta]]'' magazine. He graduated in 1954 and began work as a [[Correspondent|foreign correspondent]] for various [[London]] newspapers. He married fellow Cambridge graduate [[Claire Tomalin]] in 1955<ref>http://www.freebmd.org.uk search on Tomalin marriages post 1953</ref> and they had three daughters and two sons.<ref>http://www.freebmd.org.uk search on Tomalin/Delavenay births post 1955</ref> In spite of numerous affairs on his part (and hers),<ref>Tomalin, Claire "Several Strangers" p.8</ref> they remained together until his death.

He later co-wrote a book with Ron Hall about amateur sailor [[Donald Crowhurst]]'s failed attempt to circumnavigate the world and subsequent suicide.
His article ''[[The General Goes Zapping Charlie Cong]]'' was included in [[Tom Wolfe]]'s collection ''[[The New Journalism]]'', which was a collection of non-fiction pieces emblematic of a new movement of reporting aimed at revolutionising the field.

Tomalin's articles often began with bombastic statements on their subject matter. The most famous of these is: "The only qualities essential for real success in journalism are ratlike cunning, a plausible manner and a little literary ability".<ref>Tomalin, Nicholas "Stop the press I want to get on" ''Sunday Times Magazine'' 26 October 1969</ref>

Tomalin was killed in Israel by a Syrian [[wire-guided missile]] on 17 October 1973 while reporting on the [[Yom Kippur War]].<ref>[http://thejournalistsmemorial.rsf.org/spip.php?id_article=1297 Tomalin info at The Journalist's Memorial]</ref>

In November 2005 the journalism trade publication ''[[Press Gazette]]'' named Tomalin among its top forty 'journalists of the modern era'.<ref>[http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=32585 Press Gazette names top forty journalists of the modern era]</ref>

